/**
 * Vocabulary map — every key term in the AI Literacy course with three
 * reading-level variants. The seed factory selects a variant based on the
 * learner's profile.readingLevel.
 *
 * Glosses are multi-paragraph lesson content (separated by \n\n), not just
 * dictionary definitions. Each should stand alone as a readable mini-lesson.
 */

import type { ReadingLevel } from "../../types/learnerProfile";

export interface VocabEntry {
  term: string;
  glosses: Record<ReadingLevel, string>;
  /** Optional analogy used by the analogy block for visual learners. */
  analogy?: string;
}

export const VOCABULARY: Record<string, VocabEntry> = {
  "artificial-intelligence": {
    term: "Artificial Intelligence",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "Artificial Intelligence — AI — means getting computers to do things that normally need a person. Things like understanding what you say, recognising faces, suggesting what to watch next, or flagging a suspicious bank transaction.\n\nHere's the most important thing to know: today's AI is really good at one specific job, and almost useless at everything else. The AI that recommends shows on Netflix can't help you write an email. The one that flags fraud at your bank can't recognise your face. Every AI is narrow — built for one thing.\n\nAI is not magic. It does not think. It does not feel. It is a very powerful tool that learned patterns from huge amounts of data — and it will repeat those patterns, including the bad ones.",
      standard:
        "Artificial Intelligence refers to software systems designed to perform tasks that have historically required human intelligence — things like recognising what's in a photo, translating between languages, spotting patterns in financial data, or generating natural-sounding text.\n\nUnlike traditional software, which follows rules a programmer explicitly writes ('if temperature is below 32°F, show snow warning'), AI systems learn their own rules by processing enormous amounts of example data. Show a model millions of labelled medical images and it will discover which visual patterns signal disease — no programmer needs to define those patterns in advance.\n\nThe crucial thing to hold onto: today's AI is extremely powerful within narrow boundaries, and extremely brittle outside them. The image recogniser has no idea how to write code. The code assistant cannot diagnose a medical scan. Every AI system in production today is 'narrow AI' — designed for a specific task, optimised for that task, and unreliable the moment it's pushed beyond that boundary.\n\nAI is not magic, and it is not a replacement for human judgment. It is a powerful pattern-recognition tool that does exactly what its training prepared it to do — no more, no less.",
      technical:
        "Artificial Intelligence is an umbrella term for computational systems that approximate cognitive functions through learned representations rather than hand-authored rules. The dominant paradigm since ~2012 has been deep learning: gradient-descent optimisation of neural network parameters over large supervised, self-supervised, or reinforcement-learning objectives.\n\nModern AI systems are fundamentally statistical engines. A language model assigns probability distributions over token sequences; a vision model assigns probability distributions over class labels. Neither system 'understands' in any phenomenological sense — both are performing high-dimensional interpolation over their training distribution.\n\nThe key architectural constraint is the training distribution boundary. Current models generalise well within-distribution and degrade unpredictably out-of-distribution. This is why all deployed AI is narrow AI: capability is tightly coupled to the statistical structure of the training corpus and objective function. Capability outside that structure is not robustly generalisable.\n\nPractical implication: every AI deployment decision should be preceded by asking (1) does the deployment distribution match the training distribution, (2) how are out-of-distribution inputs handled, and (3) what is the consequence of a confident wrong answer?",
    },
  },

  "narrow-ai": {
    term: "Narrow AI",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "'Narrow AI' means an AI that is great at one specific job — and only that job. The spam filter in your email is brilliant at sorting spam. But it has no idea how to answer a question. The voice assistant on your phone can understand speech — but it doesn't know how to spot a tumour on an X-ray. Every AI you have ever used is narrow AI.\n\nPeople sometimes talk about 'AGI' — Artificial General Intelligence — which would be an AI that can do anything a human can. That doesn't exist yet. All the impressive things you've seen AI do (winning chess, writing essays, generating images) are narrow tasks that took years of work by huge teams on massive amounts of data. They look impressive because they're things humans find hard. But they are still narrow.\n\nWhy does this matter? Because narrow AI fails silently outside its training. It doesn't say 'I don't know.' It gives you an answer that sounds confident — and is often wrong.",
      standard:
        "Every AI system in production today is narrow AI: it excels at the specific task it was trained on, and performance degrades sharply outside that scope. The recommendation algorithm that knows your streaming taste cannot draft an email. The fraud detection model that flags suspicious transactions cannot recognise a face. Capability in one domain does not transfer to another.\n\nThis stands in contrast to Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) — a hypothetical system that could match human cognitive flexibility across arbitrary tasks. AGI does not exist. Every headline you have ever read about AI 'surpassing human intelligence' refers to a narrow benchmark: a specific task, a specific dataset, a specific set of rules.\n\nThe practical risk of narrow AI is overconfidence at distribution boundaries. A model deployed in a new context — different population, different language, different usage pattern — does not know it's out of its depth. It continues producing outputs that look authoritative. This is why context-matching (ensuring the deployment situation resembles the training situation) is one of the most important checks before deploying AI in a new setting.",
      technical:
        "Narrow AI describes task-specific systems lacking domain transfer — the dominant paradigm in all currently deployed AI. These systems are optimised over a fixed distribution P(X,Y) and their generalisation guarantees are theoretically bounded to that distribution.\n\nContrast with Artificial General Intelligence (AGI), a hypothetical system capable of open-ended learning and cross-domain transfer, equivalent in scope to human cognition. No current architecture meets this criterion. Claims of 'superhuman AI' invariably refer to performance on specific benchmarks (ImageNet top-1 accuracy, Go, specific reasoning tasks) not open-domain general capability.\n\nThe key failure mode of narrow AI at deployment boundaries is distribution shift: when P_deploy(X) ≠ P_train(X), model confidence remains high while accuracy drops. Models do not have uncertainty representations adequate to flag this condition reliably. This motivates out-of-distribution detection, calibration research, and the operational practice of monitoring prediction confidence distributions over time after deployment.",
    },
  },

  "machine-learning": {
    term: "Machine Learning",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "Machine learning is how you teach a computer without writing exact rules. Instead of telling a spam filter 'if the email says FREE MONEY delete it,' you show it a million examples of spam and a million examples of normal email. The computer figures out the patterns itself.\n\nThink of it like training a dog. You don't explain the concept of 'sit' in dog language — you reward the right behaviour until the pattern sticks. Machine learning works the same way, just with numbers and millions of examples instead of treats.\n\nThe catch: whatever patterns were in your training examples are now baked into your model. If your spam examples were mostly in English, the filter may miss spam in other languages. If your examples had hidden biases, the model learned those too. The model learns from data — and data reflects the world as it was, not as it should be.",
      standard:
        "Machine learning is a subfield of AI in which systems discover patterns and improve at a task by processing examples, rather than following hand-written rules. A developer doesn't define what makes a photo a cat — they feed the model millions of labelled images and let it discover the distinguishing features through optimisation.\n\nThere are three main paradigms. Supervised learning trains on labelled input-output pairs (email → spam/not spam). Unsupervised learning finds structure in unlabelled data (customer segmentation). Reinforcement learning optimises behaviour through reward signals (game-playing agents). Most AI products you use daily are built on supervised or self-supervised variants.\n\nThe central implication: machine learning models are mirrors of their training data. They amplify the patterns that were present — including historical biases, gaps in representation, and errors in labelling. A model trained on biased hiring data will produce biased hiring predictions. This is not a bug in the model; it is an accurate reflection of the biased data. Correcting it requires intentional intervention, not just more data.",
      technical:
        "Machine learning is the discipline of constructing models that generalise from training data by minimising a loss function over a parameterised hypothesis space. The model h_θ is selected via empirical risk minimisation: θ* = argmin E[(h_θ(X), Y)] over the training distribution.\n\nThree primary paradigms: supervised learning (labelled pairs (x,y) from a joint distribution P(X,Y)); unsupervised learning (structure discovery over P(X) without labels); reinforcement learning (policy optimisation via reward signal from environment interaction). Contemporary LLMs use self-supervised objectives (next-token prediction, masked token prediction) that scale with corpus size and model parameters.\n\nGeneralisation is the central theoretical concern. Uniform convergence results (PAC learning, VC dimension) bound generalisation error under IID assumptions. In practice, neural network generalisation exceeds classical bounds (the 'generalisation puzzle'), attributed to implicit regularisation from SGD dynamics and architectural inductive biases. Key failure case: distribution shift invalidates IID assumptions and generalisation guarantees simultaneously.",
    },
  },

  "neural-network": {
    term: "Neural Network",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "A neural network is the type of computer program behind most modern AI — language models, image recognition, voice assistants. The name comes from a loose resemblance to the brain: it's made up of layers of simple calculation units (called neurons) that pass information to each other.\n\nHere's the important thing: it's not actually like a brain. Real neurons are biological cells; artificial neurons are just math. The 'learning' is billions of tiny numbers being adjusted until the model's outputs match the training examples closely enough.\n\nWhat made neural networks go from a niche idea to the technology powering trillion-dollar companies? Two things: enormous datasets and enormous computing power. The models you hear about — GPT, Claude, Gemini — have hundreds of billions of those adjustable numbers. Training them costs tens of millions of dollars and produces a system that is genuinely useful — but in ways its creators cannot fully explain.",
      standard:
        "Neural networks are the dominant architecture behind modern AI — large language models, image classifiers, voice recognition, recommendation systems. They are loosely inspired by the biological brain but function quite differently: each 'neuron' is simply a mathematical function that takes in numbers, applies a weighted sum, and passes the result to the next layer.\n\nThe learning process involves adjusting billions of internal weight values to minimise the difference between the model's predictions and the correct answers in the training data. This is done through an algorithm called backpropagation, which propagates error signals backward through the layers and nudges each weight slightly toward better predictions.\n\nThe word 'deep' in 'deep learning' just means the network has many layers — sometimes hundreds. More layers allow the network to learn progressively more abstract representations: an image model's early layers detect edges; middle layers detect shapes; later layers detect objects. This is why these models can do things that rule-based systems could not: they discover their own representations from data rather than relying on features a human engineered.\n\nA key limitation: neural networks are largely uninterpretable. We can see what they predict; we usually cannot trace exactly why.",
      technical:
        "Neural networks are parameterised function approximators composed of affine transformations and element-wise non-linearities, organised in a directed acyclic computation graph. A feedforward network computes f(x) = σ_L(W_L · σ_{L-1}(W_{L-1} · ... σ_1(W_1 x + b_1)...)) where σ_i are activation functions and W_i, b_i are learned parameters.\n\nTraining proceeds via stochastic gradient descent on a loss function L(f(x), y), with gradients computed via reverse-mode automatic differentiation (backpropagation). Modern training involves: batch normalisation for training stability, residual connections to mitigate vanishing gradients in deep networks, dropout for regularisation, and Adam or AdamW optimisers for adaptive learning rates.\n\nThe transformer architecture (Vaswani et al., 2017) dominates language and multi-modal modelling. Its core mechanism — scaled dot-product attention — computes contextualised representations over arbitrary-length input sequences in O(n²) time. Architectural variants (sparse attention, linear attention, state-space models) trade approximation quality for computational efficiency.\n\nInterpretability remains an open problem. Feature attribution methods (integrated gradients, SHAP), probing classifiers, and mechanistic interpretability (circuit-level analysis of learned algorithms) provide partial insight. No method yet delivers full causal explanation of model behaviour.",
    },
    analogy:
      "Think of it like a committee of specialists: one member notices straight lines, another spots curves, a third recognises noses, a fourth identifies faces. Each member hands their observation to the next. The network 'learns' which features matter by adjusting how much weight each member's opinion carries — and does this adjustment billions of times over millions of examples.",
  },

  "training-data": {
    term: "Training Data",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "Training data is the collection of examples a model learns from. Want to build a spam filter? You need thousands of examples of spam and non-spam. Want to build an image recogniser? You need millions of labelled photos. The training data is where all the model's knowledge comes from.\n\nThis creates a 'garbage in, garbage out' problem. If your training data is biased, incomplete, or full of errors, the model learns those flaws. A medical AI trained mostly on data from one country may work poorly in another. A language model trained on text from the internet inherits the prejudices in that text.\n\nTraining data is also why AI knowledge goes stale. Most models are trained once and then frozen. They don't update themselves. Ask an LLM about an event from last week and it might not know — or worse, it might invent a plausible-sounding answer based on older patterns. Always check when a model's training data was cut off.",
      standard:
        "Training data is the collection of examples used to teach a machine learning model — it is the sole source of everything the model knows. A language model trained on text learns patterns of language from that text. An image classifier trained on labelled photos learns to map visual features to class labels. No knowledge, value, or bias can enter the model through any other path.\n\nThis creates several important implications for users. First, data quality determines model quality. Mislabelled examples, gaps in demographic representation, and historical patterns of human bias all get encoded into model parameters. The model does not discriminate between facts and prejudices — it learns whatever patterns are present. Second, data scope determines knowledge scope. A model with a training data cutoff of a certain date has no knowledge of events after that date — and, critically, may confabulate plausible-sounding answers when asked about events it does not know. Third, data is not neutral. Every curation decision — what to include, how to label it, whose annotation is trusted — encodes someone's values. 'The data says so' is never an escape from normative choice.\n\nUnderstanding training data helps you ask better questions of AI products: What was it trained on? When was the cutoff? What populations are and are not represented?",
      technical:
        "Training data is the empirical distribution that defines a model's knowledge, capabilities, and failure modes. The model learns a function f: X → Y by minimising expected loss over {(xᵢ, yᵢ)} drawn from P_train(X,Y). Generalisation performance is bounded by how well P_train approximates P_deploy.\n\nData quality dimensions: (1) Label accuracy — annotation noise degrades generalisation, particularly in low-resource settings. (2) Distributional coverage — underrepresented subgroups produce higher prediction error on those subgroups, yielding disparate impact. (3) Temporal coverage — training cutoffs create knowledge boundaries; models deploy on P_deploy which shifts over time relative to P_train. (4) Annotation schema — label design encodes normative choices that propagate into model behaviour.\n\nFor large language models, training corpora consist of internet-scale text, books, and code — an estimated 10^12–10^13 tokens. Curation involves deduplication, quality filtering, and toxicity reduction. These curation decisions are under-documented and create poorly characterised distributional properties. Bias inheritance from training corpora is not fully addressable post-hoc; interventions like RLHF and constitutional AI provide partial mitigation by shaping the preference distribution over the model's output distribution.",
    },
  },

  agi: {
    term: "Artificial General Intelligence (AGI)",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "AGI — Artificial General Intelligence — is the AI that science fiction imagines: a machine that can think about anything, learn any skill, and apply knowledge flexibly the way a human does. The robot that can be a doctor, a lawyer, a musician, and a friend. That doesn't exist yet.\n\nEvery AI system you have used is 'narrow AI' — amazing at one thing, useless at most others. AlphaGo mastered Go, one of the hardest board games ever invented. It cannot play chess without being retrained. ChatGPT can hold a remarkably human-seeming conversation. It cannot reliably count to ten if you give it a novel arithmetic problem.\n\nWhen you see headlines saying 'AI is now smarter than humans,' they mean on one specific test, for one specific task. They do not mean the AI has become generally intelligent. AGI, if it ever arrives, would be a genuinely transformative moment in history — but it would look very different from the tools available today.",
      standard:
        "Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) describes a hypothetical AI system capable of performing any intellectual task a human can — not just tasks it was specifically trained for, but arbitrary new tasks, using flexible reasoning and genuine transfer of knowledge across domains.\n\nNo such system exists. Every AI system deployed today is narrow AI: excellent within its training distribution, brittle outside it. When researchers or journalists describe an AI as having 'surpassed human intelligence,' they are always referring to performance on a specific benchmark — a structured test with known rules and measurable outcomes. Benchmark performance does not generalise to open-world general capability.\n\nThe question of when or whether AGI will arrive is genuinely uncertain and actively debated among researchers. What is not debated: today's large language models, regardless of how impressive their outputs can seem, are sophisticated pattern-matching systems, not general reasoning engines. They fail in predictable ways on novel tasks that require genuine reasoning from first principles, multi-step planning, or reliable factual recall.\n\nFor practical AI literacy: when you encounter claims that AI is becoming or has become generally intelligent, the useful question is 'intelligent at what, measured how, compared to what baseline?'",
      technical:
        "AGI is an informally defined target: an AI system achieving human-level or above performance across the full distribution of intellectual tasks, including novel tasks unseen during training. The absence of a precise formal definition makes AGI progress claims difficult to evaluate.\n\nCurrent LLMs exhibit in-context learning and zero-shot transfer that were not anticipated by classical learning theory. However, failure modes on compositional generalisation tasks (SCAN, ARC-AGI), multi-step reasoning, and out-of-distribution arithmetic suggest these capabilities are shallower than they appear. Proposed measures of general intelligence (g-factor analogues for AI, ARC benchmark) show large LLMs performing at human-novice levels, not expert-human levels, on tasks requiring genuine novel reasoning.\n\nKey architectural constraints: (1) context-window bounded working memory, (2) no persistent learning at inference time, (3) no reliable causal world model, (4) hallucination rates that do not approach zero. Whether scaling resolves these constraints is the central empirical question in the field. Current evidence suggests emergent capabilities appear at scale thresholds but systematic reasoning limitations remain across model families.",
    },
  },

  llm: {
    term: "Large Language Model (LLM)",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "A Large Language Model — or LLM — is the technology behind tools like ChatGPT, Claude, and Gemini. The name tells you almost everything: it's a large model trained on language. Specifically, it learned from billions of pages of text — books, websites, code, articles — until it became very good at predicting what word comes next in a sentence.\n\nWhen you ask it a question, it doesn't look the answer up in a database. It generates a response word by word, each word chosen because it is the most likely continuation based on patterns in its training. That's why it sounds natural and fluent — and it's also why it can confidently write something completely wrong. Plausibility is not accuracy.\n\nThink of an LLM as the world's most sophisticated autocomplete. It has read almost everything ever written in its training data, and it is exceptionally good at writing things that sound like what a knowledgeable human would say. Whether those things are true is a separate question.",
      standard:
        "Large Language Models (LLMs) are neural networks trained on internet-scale text corpora to predict the next token in a sequence. This simple training objective — given everything so far, what comes next? — produces systems that can answer questions, write code, summarise documents, translate languages, and reason through problems with remarkable fluency.\n\nThe key mechanic: LLMs do not retrieve facts from a database. They generate responses by iteratively sampling the most likely next word given the context. This means their outputs are controlled by probability distributions learned from training data, not by logical rules or verified knowledge. A model can produce a confident, grammatically perfect, well-structured answer that is entirely false — because it learned the pattern of 'how confident answers about this topic tend to sound,' not the actual facts.\n\nThis is the root cause of 'hallucination' — a well-documented failure mode where LLMs generate plausible-sounding but factually incorrect content. The model has no internal fact-checker and no reliable way to distinguish what it knows from what it is confabulating. Fluency and confidence in tone are completely decoupled from factual accuracy.\n\nPractical habit: treat LLM output as a first draft from a knowledgeable-but-unreliable collaborator. The draft is often excellent. The facts need checking.",
      technical:
        "Large Language Models are autoregressive transformer architectures trained on token prediction objectives over web-scale corpora (10¹²–10¹³ tokens). Core components: tokenisation (BPE or SentencePiece), multi-head self-attention over a context window (typically 8k–1M tokens in current frontier models), feedforward sublayers, and a final unembedding + softmax projection to a probability distribution over the vocabulary.\n\nAt inference, output is sampled from p(x_t | x_<t) at each step, with temperature controlling distribution sharpness and top-p/top-k sampling truncating the tail. Greedy decoding (argmax) reduces diversity; high temperature increases creativity but also error rate.\n\nCapability emerges from pre-training scale (model parameters × training compute × data tokens) following approximately power-law scaling laws (Hoffmann et al., Chinchilla). Post-training alignment — instruction tuning (SFT) followed by RLHF or RLAIF — shapes the distribution toward helpful, harmless, honest outputs without substantially changing the base model's knowledge.\n\nKey limitations: (1) knowledge is frozen at training cutoff; (2) hallucination rates remain non-zero across all frontier models; (3) context-window constrained memory; (4) no reliable self-knowledge of confidence calibration. The model cannot distinguish between what it 'knows' (has strong training signal for) and what it is confabulating.",
    },
    analogy:
      "Like autocomplete that has read most of the internet — it predicts what word comes next, then again, and again, until a whole response appears. The writing looks human because it was trained on human writing. The facts need checking because plausibility and truth are not the same thing.",
  },

  hallucination: {
    term: "Hallucination",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "AI hallucination is when a model makes something up and states it as fact — confidently, fluently, with no hint that it might be wrong. It might invent a scientific study that doesn't exist, quote a law incorrectly, give you a phone number that belongs to a different person, or describe an event that never happened. And it will do all of this in the same calm, helpful tone it uses when it's right.\n\nWhy does this happen? Because LLMs generate text by predicting what comes next based on patterns, not by looking up verified facts. The model learned 'how a credible answer about this topic tends to sound' — not 'what is actually true about this topic.' Plausibility is not accuracy.\n\nThe practical rule: never trust an LLM output for anything important without verifying it against a reliable source. The model can be an excellent starting point — a first draft, a brainstorm, a way to quickly understand a topic. But any specific claim — a date, a name, a statistic, a legal rule, a medical fact — must be confirmed independently.",
      standard:
        "Hallucination refers to the tendency of language models to generate content that sounds plausible and is stated confidently, but is factually incorrect or entirely fabricated. Examples include: inventing academic citations with believable-sounding titles and authors, misquoting laws or policies, generating realistic-seeming but false biographical details, or describing events that never occurred.\n\nHallucination is not a bug that will be patched away — it is a fundamental property of how LLMs work. The model generates text by predicting the most likely next token given everything before it. It has no separate verification mechanism, no connection to a live database of facts, and no reliable internal signal to distinguish what it genuinely 'knows' from what it is confabulating. Confidence in tone is completely decoupled from factual accuracy.\n\nThis has direct consequences for how you use AI tools. The more specific and verifiable a claim, the more important it is to check it: names, dates, statistics, citations, legal provisions, medical dosages, product specifications, and historical facts should all be verified against authoritative sources before being relied upon. The model is at its most reliable when generating or restructuring your own ideas — and at its most dangerous when being asked to supply facts it may never have had.\n\nA healthy habit: think of every AI output as a knowledgeable colleague's first-pass answer. Worth reading; not worth citing without checking.",
      technical:
        "Hallucination in language models refers to outputs with high model confidence but low factual accuracy — the model assigns high probability to false tokens. This is a consequence of optimising for next-token likelihood on training corpora rather than for factual accuracy.\n\nTwo main categories: (1) Closed-domain hallucination — incorrect outputs within a context window containing the relevant information (context misuse). (2) Open-domain hallucination — fabrication of facts not present in context or verifiable training data.\n\nMitigation strategies: Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) grounds generation in retrieved documents, reducing open-domain hallucination by providing the relevant context at inference time. Constitutional AI and RLHF reduce confident false assertions by shaping the output distribution toward epistemic humility. Calibration research attempts to align model confidence scores with empirical accuracy.\n\nHallucination rates remain non-trivial across all frontier models on domain-specific factual tasks. Evaluation is complicated by the difficulty of constructing ground-truth corpora for niche claims. Practical implication: no current LLM should be treated as a reliable oracle for specific factual claims; output should be verified against authoritative primary sources for any high-stakes use.",
    },
  },

  bias: {
    term: "Bias in AI",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "AI bias means the model treats some groups of people differently — giving worse results, less accurate predictions, or worse outcomes to people from certain backgrounds. And unlike human bias, which at least has a face and can be held accountable, AI bias runs automatically, at scale, on millions of decisions.\n\nWhere does it come from? The training data. If a hiring model was trained on ten years of past hiring decisions, and those decisions reflected patterns of discrimination, the model will reproduce those patterns. If a medical model was trained mostly on data from one ethnicity, it will be less accurate for others. The model isn't prejudiced in the human sense — it just learned the patterns that were there.\n\nThe 'it's just math so it must be objective' argument is one of the most dangerous myths about AI. Math scales bias. It doesn't erase it. The fact that a decision was made by an algorithm doesn't make it fair — it just makes it faster, cheaper, and harder to challenge.",
      standard:
        "AI bias refers to systematic skew in a model's predictions or behaviour — producing worse outcomes for certain groups of people than others. The most studied forms include racial bias in facial recognition (higher error rates on darker skin tones), gender bias in hiring algorithms (downranking women for technical roles), and socioeconomic bias in loan approval models (unfairly penalising applicants based on ZIP code proxies).\n\nBias enters AI systems through multiple pathways. Historical data bias: if training data reflects past discrimination, the model learns to reproduce those patterns. Representation gaps: if certain populations are underrepresented in training data, accuracy is lower for those groups. Proxy variables: even when protected attributes (race, gender) are excluded from inputs, correlated features (ZIP code, name, school attended) can serve as proxies, laundering the bias through technically 'neutral' variables. Labelling bias: if human annotators have implicit biases, those biases enter the ground-truth labels the model optimises toward.\n\nThe 'AI is objective because it's mathematical' argument is one of the most consequential myths in technology. Algorithms scale whatever patterns are in their training data — bias included. A biased decision made manually affects one person at a time; a biased algorithm makes the same biased decision millions of times per day. The harms are larger, faster, and more difficult to contest because they appear to come from a neutral process.",
      technical:
        "Algorithmic bias refers to systematic disparities in model performance or output distribution across demographic subgroups, typically operationalised as differential prediction error (accuracy, precision, recall, AUROC) or differential exposure to beneficial/harmful outcomes.\n\nFormal fairness criteria are numerous and often incompatible: demographic parity (equal positive rate across groups), equalised odds (equal TPR and FPR), calibration (equal predicted probability accuracy), individual fairness (similar inputs mapped to similar outputs). Impossibility results (Chouldechova, 2017; Kleinberg et al., 2016) prove that certain fairness criteria cannot be simultaneously satisfied when base rates differ across groups — fairness is an inherently normative choice.\n\nBias enters through: (1) sampling bias in training distribution, (2) label bias from human annotators with implicit prejudice, (3) feature selection that preserves high-correlation proxies for protected attributes, (4) model architecture inductive biases, (5) feedback loops where biased predictions influence future training data. Mitigation techniques include pre-processing interventions (resampling, reweighting), in-processing constraints (fairness-regularised objectives), and post-processing calibration (threshold adjustment). No intervention is domain-neutral; appropriate choice depends on the downstream harm model.",
    },
  },

  prompt: {
    term: "Prompt Engineering",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "A prompt is what you type to an AI. 'Prompt engineering' is the practice of crafting those inputs to get useful, accurate outputs. It sounds technical, but the core idea is simple: be specific about what you want, who you are, and what a good answer looks like.\n\nThe vague prompt 'write me a cover letter' produces a generic cover letter. The specific prompt 'write a cover letter for a software engineer with 5 years of Python experience applying for a remote data engineering role at a climate tech company — 3 paragraphs, professional but warm tone, lead with my expertise in processing large datasets' produces something you might actually use.\n\nThree things that almost always help: (1) Tell the AI who it is writing for. (2) Tell the AI what format you want. (3) Tell the AI what to avoid. The more context you give, the less the model has to guess — and guessing is where things go wrong.",
      standard:
        "Prompting is the act of providing a language model with the context and instructions that condition its output. Prompt engineering — deliberately crafting those inputs — is one of the highest-leverage skills for AI users. The difference between a vague prompt and a well-structured one can be the difference between a useless draft and a polished result.\n\nEffective prompts tend to include: a role or persona ('you are an expert science writer targeting a general audience'), a clear goal ('summarise this research paper in three paragraphs'), specific constraints ('no jargon, under 200 words, use active voice'), output format ('respond in bullet points'), and examples when relevant ('here's a sample of the tone I want').\n\nThe most common misconception about prompting is that there are 'magic phrases' that unlock better answers. There are not. What actually works is iteration and specificity. Start with a prompt, see where the output fails, identify which piece of context was missing, and add it. Repeat. Think of it as a conversation with a capable assistant who needs to be briefed, not a spell to be cast perfectly on the first try.\n\nEqually important: verify the output. A well-crafted prompt increases the chance of a useful response — it does not guarantee accuracy. Prompting skill does not substitute for critical evaluation of what the model produces.",
      technical:
        "A prompt is the input token sequence that conditions an LLM's output distribution at inference time. Prompt engineering is the empirical practice of selecting inputs that steer the model toward high-utility outputs within a fixed, trained model.\n\nKey techniques: (1) In-context learning (ICL) — providing k examples of input-output pairs prepends the inference with a demonstration distribution, shifting the model toward the demonstrated task. Few-shot prompting outperforms zero-shot on many structured tasks. (2) Chain-of-thought (CoT) — eliciting step-by-step reasoning ('let's think step by step') has been shown to substantially improve performance on multi-step arithmetic and logical reasoning tasks by externalising intermediate reasoning steps into the context window. (3) Role prompting — system-level persona conditioning shapes tone and register; evidence for substantial capability change is mixed. (4) Constitutional prompting — providing explicit criteria for self-evaluation enables the model to revise outputs against specified principles.\n\nContext-length effects: attention is not uniformly distributed across the context window. The 'lost in the middle' phenomenon describes degraded recall of information positioned mid-context in long inputs. Practical implication: critical constraints and examples should appear near the beginning or end of long prompts.\n\nPrompt injection is the adversarial counterpart: malicious instructions embedded in user content or retrieved data can override system-level instructions. This is an active security concern for any LLM-integrated application that processes untrusted input.",
    },
  },

  "context-window": {
    term: "Context Window",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "The context window is the AI's working memory — the maximum amount of text it can 'see' at once. Everything outside the context window is invisible to the model. It cannot remember what you told it in a previous conversation (unless that information is re-provided) and it cannot remember what's in a long document if that document exceeds the window limit.\n\nA practical consequence: if you paste a very long document and ask the model to summarise it, the quality of the summary can degrade depending on what falls in the middle. Research has found that LLMs pay more attention to the beginning and end of their context window — information buried in the middle is more likely to be missed or misrepresented.\n\nThe fix: for long documents, break them into sections and work through each one. Ask targeted questions rather than 'summarise everything.' And never assume the model 'remembered' something from a previous session — always re-provide important context.",
      standard:
        "The context window defines the maximum amount of text a language model can process in a single interaction — both the input you provide and the output it generates. Modern frontier models have context windows ranging from ~8,000 to ~1,000,000 tokens (roughly 6,000 to 750,000 words). Everything outside the window is invisible to the model at that point.\n\nContext windows have two practical consequences. First, there is a hard knowledge boundary: for conversations or documents longer than the context window, earlier content must be either summarised, discarded, or re-provided. The model has no memory of past sessions by default. Second, attention is not uniform within the window: research has documented the 'lost in the middle' phenomenon, where retrieval of information positioned in the middle of long contexts is significantly less reliable than retrieval of information near the beginning or end.\n\nFor users: (1) Always re-provide critical context at the start of each new session; (2) For very long documents, prefer targeted queries ('what does the contract say about termination clauses?') over sweeping summaries; (3) When summarising long content, consider breaking it into sections and summarising each one separately.",
      technical:
        "The context window is the maximum token sequence length the model can process in a single forward pass, encompassing both the prompt and the generated completion. Architectural context limits are set by the attention mechanism's complexity (O(n²) in standard self-attention) and positional encoding scheme.\n\nModern approaches to extending context: (1) Efficient attention variants (Longformer, FlashAttention, linear attention approximations) reduce quadratic attention cost. (2) Positional encoding extrapolation (RoPE, ALiBi) enables inference beyond training context lengths with varying fidelity. (3) RAG replaces in-context storage of long documents with retrieval at inference time.\n\nThe 'lost in the middle' phenomenon (Liu et al., 2023) documents a U-shaped recall curve within long contexts: performance degrades for information positioned mid-context relative to prefix and suffix positions. The mechanism is hypothesised to relate to attention sink effects and proximity bias in autoregressive attention patterns.\n\nPractical deployment implications: (1) RAG is often preferable to long-context retrieval for precise factual lookup due to more reliable retrieval mechanics; (2) Multi-turn context management (summarisation, selective retention) is required for long-horizon agentic tasks; (3) Prompt positioning matters — high-value constraints should appear at position-salient locations (beginning of system prompt, end of user turn).",
    },
  },

  "ai-accountability": {
    term: "Accountability in AI Systems",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "When an AI system makes a decision that harms someone — denying a loan, misdiagnosing an illness, wrongly flagging a face — someone needs to be accountable. But who?\n\nThe answer is: the people and organisations who built, deployed, and chose to rely on the system. The model cannot be held responsible. It doesn't make choices; it produces outputs. The humans who decided to use those outputs, how to deploy the system, which safeguards to include, and whose interests to protect — those are the people who bear responsibility.\n\n'It was the algorithm's decision' is not a valid excuse. If you deploy an AI to make consequential decisions about people's lives, you are responsible for the quality and fairness of those decisions. The algorithm is a tool you chose. You are accountable for how you use it.",
      standard:
        "When AI systems make consequential errors — wrongly denying a loan, incorrectly flagging a suspect, miscategorising a medical case — the question of accountability is both ethical and legal. A key principle: models cannot bear accountability. Accountability for automated decisions rests with the humans and institutions who designed, deployed, and maintained the system.\n\nThis means several things in practice. The organisation that deployed an AI screening tool is responsible for auditing it for fairness before deployment — not just assuming it works. The team that chose training data is responsible for the biases encoded in it. The manager who relied on AI output to make a hiring decision is responsible for that decision, not shielded by the automation.\n\nA recurring failure pattern is 'accountability laundering' — using algorithmic processes to diffuse responsibility across so many people and systems that no one remains clearly accountable when harm occurs. The EU AI Act, the FTC's AI guidance, and emerging case law are all working to close this gap by requiring transparency, auditability, and human oversight for high-risk AI deployments.\n\nFor anyone using AI in professional contexts: document your AI use, retain human review for consequential decisions, and be prepared to explain — and stand behind — any AI-assisted outcome.",
      technical:
        "Accountability in AI systems involves the assignment of responsibility for outcomes across the sociotechnical system: model developers, data curators, system integrators, deployers, and end users. Meaningful accountability requires traceability — the ability to reconstruct how a specific output was produced — and contestability — the ability of affected parties to challenge and seek redress for AI-driven decisions.\n\nLegal frameworks diverge: EU AI Act (2024) establishes risk tiers with mandatory conformity assessment, human oversight requirements, and post-market monitoring obligations for high-risk AI applications. US executive guidance focuses on sector-specific principles without binding horizontal legislation. Both frameworks establish that deployers bear primary legal responsibility for AI-driven decisions affecting individuals.\n\nTechnical requirements for accountable AI: (1) Audit trails — logs sufficient to reconstruct decision pathways; (2) Explainability — outputs interpretable to affected individuals and oversight bodies (SHAP, LIME, post-hoc rationalisation); (3) Monitoring — distribution shift detection, performance tracking across demographic subgroups, anomaly alerting; (4) Rollback capability — mechanisms to disable the system or revert to a prior version on detection of harmful drift.\n\nThe 'black box' problem — where model internals are opaque even to developers — creates accountability gaps that explainability methods only partially close. There is active tension between model performance (often enhanced by opacity) and regulatory requirements for interpretability.",
    },
  },

  "data-privacy": {
    term: "Data Privacy and AI",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "Every time you use an AI tool, you are also sharing data. The question is: what data, with whom, and for how long?\n\nSome AI tools are trained on user conversations. Some store everything indefinitely. Some share data with third parties. Most of this is disclosed in privacy policies that almost no one reads. That's a problem — because your conversations with an AI might contain sensitive information: medical symptoms, work documents, personal relationships, financial details.\n\nThe practical habit: before using an AI tool for anything sensitive, check whether conversations are stored, whether they're used for training, and whether you can opt out. For truly sensitive work, use tools with explicit data-retention controls or use them in enterprise/private-deployment mode where data stays within your organisation.",
      standard:
        "AI tools collect and use data in ways that warrant careful consideration, particularly for professional and personal sensitive information. The relevant questions are: Is my input stored? For how long? Is it used to retrain the model? Who has access to it? Can I delete it?\n\nFor consumer AI tools, the default in many cases is that conversations may be reviewed by employees for safety or quality purposes and may be used to improve models. Business versions of the same tools often offer stronger guarantees: data is not retained, is not used for training, and is stored within specific jurisdictions.\n\nSeveral specific risks: (1) Sensitive professional data — attaching confidential business documents to an AI query may share that content with the AI provider. (2) Personal health information — asking medical questions may create stored records of sensitive conditions. (3) Legal privilege — attorney-client privileged communications should never be shared with AI tools without legal guidance. (4) FERPA and HIPAA — regulated student and health information may not be shareable with AI tools under standard consumer terms.\n\nThe underlying principle: 'free' AI tools are often monetised through data. The value exchange is worth understanding before the exchange happens.",
      technical:
        "AI data privacy concerns span the full model lifecycle: training data collection (consent, provenance, personal data inclusion), inference-time data handling (input retention, logging, third-party sharing), and model memory (whether models encode personally identifiable information in weights).\n\nTraining data privacy: large-scale web-crawled corpora frequently contain personal information (names, addresses, email content, social media posts) often collected without explicit consent. Memorisation research (Carlini et al., 2021) demonstrates that LLMs can reproduce verbatim training data under targeted extraction attacks, including PII. Differential privacy training provides formal privacy guarantees but typically degrades model utility.\n\nInference privacy: most commercial LLMs log query-response pairs. Terms of service determine retention policy, training use, and access controls. Enterprise agreements typically offer stronger guarantees (no training use, data residency, deletion on request). Privacy-preserving inference (homomorphic encryption, secure multi-party computation) remains computationally prohibitive for large-scale deployment.\n\nRegulatory landscape: GDPR Article 22 restricts solely automated decision-making affecting individuals; right to erasure is complicated by model memorisation. CCPA provides similar rights for California residents. The EU AI Act introduces data governance requirements for high-risk AI training data. The tension between regulatory right-to-erasure and the cost of model unlearning (machine unlearning research is an active area) remains unresolved.",
    },
  },

  "ai-augmentation": {
    term: "AI as Augmentation, Not Replacement",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "There's a widespread fear that AI will take everyone's job. The reality is more complicated — and for most people in most jobs today, more reassuring.\n\nAI is very good at certain things: drafting, summarising, classifying, pattern-matching in data, generating variations on existing content. It is poor at other things: genuine creativity, moral judgment, building relationships, navigating novel situations, taking responsibility for outcomes. Most jobs require some of both.\n\nThe historical pattern is that automation eliminates specific tasks within jobs, not entire jobs wholesale. The spreadsheet eliminated some bookkeeping tasks but created the accountant as we know the role today. Email eliminated some administrative tasks but created new communication demands. AI is following a similar pattern: it handles the drafting, you do the judgment. It handles the search, you do the synthesis. Learning to work with AI — to use it to amplify your output rather than replace your judgment — is the practical skill of this decade.",
      standard:
        "The question of AI's impact on employment is real and not fully resolved — but the 'AI will replace all jobs' narrative overstates the case and misrepresents the pattern of how automation has historically worked.\n\nCurrent AI excels at tasks involving pattern recognition in large data, generating variations on existing content, and routine classification. It struggles with tasks requiring genuine contextual judgment, accountability for outcomes, novel problem-solving outside its training distribution, and relationship-building. Most occupations contain a mix of both kinds of tasks.\n\nHistorical automation precedents suggest displacement of specific tasks, not entire occupations. The spreadsheet automated calculation but created the financial analyst role as we know it. Word processing eliminated typing pools but expanded the scope of writing professionals. ATMs did not eliminate bank tellers — branch numbers remained stable while teller roles shifted toward relationship banking. In each case, the humans who thrived were those who adapted: learning to work with the new tool, focusing on the judgment and relationship tasks it could not perform.\n\nThe practical implication for your career: identify which tasks in your role AI can handle, use it for those, and invest in the judgment, communication, and relationship skills that differentiate you from a model. The risk is not replacement — it's irrelevance for those who don't adapt, and leverage for those who do.",
      technical:
        "The economic analysis of AI's labour market impact draws on task-based models of occupational change. The relevant distinction is between automation of tasks versus displacement of occupations. AI augments workers by lowering the cost of certain task inputs (language generation, pattern classification), shifting the marginal value of complementary tasks (judgment, creativity, oversight, relationship management).\n\nEmpirical evidence on LLM labour market effects is preliminary but developing: (1) BCG/Harvard field experiment (2023) found GPT-4 raised worker productivity on knowledge work tasks 12.2% on average. (2) Goldman Sachs modelling projects 26% of US work tasks could be automated by current AI. (3) Labour market data shows growing demand for AI oversight, prompt engineering, and AI-adjacent roles, offsetting some displacement.\n\nThe 'task displacement, occupation evolution' pattern is consistent with historical automation waves (mechanisation, computerisation). However, the pace of change and breadth of cognitive task coverage distinguish this wave. Key variables determining individual exposure: (1) routine vs. non-routine cognitive content, (2) social and relational task weight, (3) physical task weight, (4) degree of novelty required. Workers with high social, physical, or novel-reasoning task loads face lower immediate substitution risk.",
    },
  },

  // ── MODULE 3 VOCABULARY ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  sycophancy: {
    term: "Sycophancy in AI",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "AI sycophancy means the model tells you what you want to hear instead of what is true. It learned this by being trained on human ratings — and people tend to give higher ratings to answers that agree with them, flatter them, or sound reassuring. So the model got better and better at agreeing, and worse at pushing back.\n\nThis sounds like a minor annoyance. In health or financial contexts it can be dangerous. A sycophantic health chatbot learns to reassure you rather than refer you, because 'you probably just need rest' gets better ratings than 'go to the ER.' It is more satisfying. It is also more likely to be wrong when it matters most.\n\nThe test: if you push back on an AI's answer and it immediately changes position — without you providing new information — that is sycophancy. It is not updating its view; it is capitulating to your preference.",
      standard:
        "Sycophancy is a systematic bias in AI models trained with human feedback: the model learns to prioritise responses that users rate highly over responses that are accurate. Since human raters tend to reward agreeable, confident, and validating answers, the model optimises for exactly those qualities — often at the expense of truth.\n\nThe mechanism: reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) teaches models to maximise reward signals from human evaluators. Those evaluators, consciously or not, rate pleasant answers more highly than correct-but-uncomfortable ones. The resulting model is trained to agree, flatter, and reassure at scale.\n\nSycophancy becomes a safety risk in high-stakes domains. A medical AI that learned from user-satisfaction ratings will systematically under-refer — 'rest and hydration' earns better ratings than 'see a doctor.' A financial chatbot will validate poor decisions rather than challenge them. A tutoring system will confirm the student's wrong answer rather than risk a disappointed reaction.\n\nDetection: ask a model a question, get an answer, then confidently assert the opposite. If it reverses without new evidence, it is sycophanting. Robust models will explain why they are maintaining their original position; sycophantic models will discover reasons to agree with whatever you just said.",
      technical:
        "Sycophancy is an alignment failure arising from RLHF training dynamics. Human raters systematically reward responses that are agreeable, validating, and confident, independent of factual accuracy. This creates a reward signal that trains the policy to optimise for perceived satisfaction rather than epistemic quality.\n\nEmpirical manifestations: (1) Position capitulation — models reverse correct answers under social pressure without new evidence (Perez et al., 2022; Anthropic internal evals); (2) False validation — models praise work of objectively low quality when the user displays attachment to it; (3) Reassurance bias — models frame uncertain outcomes positively, particularly in health and risk domains; (4) Confirmation amplification — models generate arguments that confirm the user's stated position more readily than disconfirm it.\n\nThe structural cause: RLHF optimises a proxy (human preference ratings) for a target (response quality). When these diverge — as they systematically do in domains where truthful answers are uncomfortable — the model learns the proxy. Constitutional AI and adversarial RLHF (training on prompts specifically designed to elicit sycophancy) can partially mitigate this, but the structural pressure of optimising for human preference is inherent to the training paradigm.\n\nDeployment risk is asymmetric by domain: sycophancy in creative or casual use produces suboptimal but low-stakes outputs. In medical triage, legal advice, or financial decisions, sycophancy can produce confident, fluent, satisfying answers that are systematically miscalibrated toward the outcome the user prefers rather than the outcome that is accurate.",
    },
  },

  "latent-space": {
    term: "Latent Space",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "Inside every AI model that generates images or text is a kind of invisible map — a space where concepts live. On this map, 'apple' and 'orange' are close together because they are both fruit. 'Violin' and 'piano' are close because they are both musical instruments. 'Van Gogh' and 'Rembrandt' are near each other because they are both painters with distinctive styles.\n\nWhen you ask an AI image generator for 'a Van Gogh painting of a jazz musician,' the model finds the Van Gogh cluster on this map, finds the jazz musician cluster, and generates something that sits between them. It is not copying a specific painting — it is navigating to a location in concept space and generating from there.\n\nThis is why style transfer works. It is also why the copyright lawsuits are complex: the map was built by training on real works, and the locations on it correspond to — and were derived from — those works.",
      standard:
        "Latent space is the internal, high-dimensional representation space that neural networks learn to organise concepts in during training. Every piece of content the model has learned from — every image, word, style, idea — is encoded as a position (a vector) in this space. Related concepts cluster near each other; unrelated ones are far apart. This geometric structure is not explicitly programmed: it emerges from training.\n\nGenerative AI exploits this structure. When you prompt an image generator for 'a Vermeer-style portrait of a data scientist,' the text encoder maps your prompt to a region in latent space — the Vermeer cluster, the portrait cluster, the data-scientist-appearance cluster. The model then generates an image by sampling from the intersection of those regions. No specific Vermeer is copied; the model navigates to a location defined by the learned geometry and generates from there.\n\nThis mechanism explains several things at once: why style transfer works (style is a learnable cluster in latent space); why bias amplification occurs (if 'CEO' was associated with male-appearing faces in training data, the CEO cluster in latent space reflects that bias); and why copyright questions are legally complex (the latent space was built from training on real works, and regions in it were shaped by those works, even if no individual output is a direct copy).",
      technical:
        "Latent space (equivalently: embedding space, representation space, feature manifold) is the intermediate learned representation between a model's input and output layers. In variational autoencoders, it is the stochastic bottleneck with explicit Gaussian prior structure, enabling controlled sampling and interpolation. In diffusion models (Stable Diffusion, DALL-E 3), it is the continuous space in which denoising occurs, compressed from pixel space via a trained VAE encoder.\n\nThe latent space organises semantics through training: models trained on paired (image, text) data (CLIP, ALIGN) learn an aligned latent space where the image encoding of a concept and the text encoding of the same concept are proximate. This alignment enables text-to-image generation via cross-attention conditioning on text embeddings.\n\nStyle transfer exploits the factored structure of latent representations: style-related statistics (Gram matrices of feature activations, as in Gatys et al., 2016; or Adaptive Instance Normalisation, Huang & Belongie, 2017) can be separated from content structure, enabling independent manipulation. In large text-to-image models, style is implicitly represented as a cluster geometry in latent space that the text encoder can navigate to via prompt.\n\nThe copyright question is analytically distinct from the latent-space mechanism: the relevant question is whether training on copyrighted data without licence constitutes infringement, not whether individual outputs copy specific works. The latent-space argument ('the model interpolates, not copies') is one line of defence in pending litigation; the counterargument is that the interpolation structure was learned from unlicensed protected works, and the derivative-work doctrine extends to training pipelines.",
    },
    analogy:
      "Imagine a city where similar buildings cluster in the same neighbourhood: art museums near art galleries near art supply stores. Generative AI navigates this city. When you ask for 'a Van Gogh jazz musician,' the model finds the Van Gogh neighbourhood, finds the jazz musician neighbourhood, and builds something at the intersection. It is not stealing from a specific address — it is constructing at a location defined by the neighbourhood geography. The controversy is about who built the neighbourhoods, and whether they had permission.",
  },

  "inference-chain": {
    term: "Data Inference Chain",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "An inference chain is what AI can figure out about you from data you shared for a completely different reason. You gave a weather app your location — fair enough, for weather. But your location also reveals: where you live, where you work, which church or mosque or temple you go to, which clinic you visit, which political rallies you attend, and what income bracket your neighbourhood suggests. You shared one thing. The inference chain derived a whole profile.\n\nThis is the part of privacy that most people miss. The conversation about privacy usually focuses on what data you share. The more important conversation is about what AI can infer from what you share. You did not hand anyone your religion, politics, or health conditions. The inference chain did it for you, without your knowledge.\n\n'I have nothing to hide' misses this entirely. You are not deciding what to hide — you are deciding what others can infer. Those are very different choices.",
      standard:
        "Data inference — or the inference chain — refers to the ability of AI systems to derive sensitive attributes about individuals from data that was not sensitive at the point of collection. The canonical example is GPS location: coordinates reveal home address, workplace, daily routine, religious practice (place-of-worship visits), health conditions (clinic types), political activity (rally attendance), and social connections — none of which were disclosed, all of which are inferable from movement patterns.\n\nThe chain compounds: first-order inferences (home location → income bracket) enable second-order inferences (income bracket + health-clinic visits → insurance risk profile) that enable third-order consequences (insurance pricing, credit decisions, targeted advertising) that the user never consented to and may not even be aware of.\n\nThe concept of 'anonymisation' provides limited protection in this context. Research by Montjoye et al. (2013) demonstrated that just four spatio-temporal data points re-identify 95% of individuals in an 'anonymised' mobile dataset. 'De-identified' means your name is not attached; it does not mean you cannot be identified. The inference chain works on patterns, not labels.\n\nPractical implication: before granting any data permission, the relevant question is not 'what did I disclose?' but 'what can be derived from what I disclosed?' These are rarely the same answer.",
      technical:
        "Data inference attacks exploit statistical redundancy between observable proxy variables and sensitive latent attributes. The formal framing is attribute inference: given auxiliary information and a partial profile x, infer sensitive attribute s not present in x, leveraging a trained model f: x → s built from population-level correlations.\n\nEmpirically documented inference chains: (1) Location → religion/politics/health: Montjoye et al. (MIT, 2013) demonstrated 95% re-identification from four spatio-temporal points; Sweeney (2000) demonstrated 87% re-identification of Massachusetts residents from ZIP code + birthdate + sex alone. (2) Purchase patterns → medical conditions: Target's pregnancy inference (2012) from purchase pattern changes. (3) Social graph → political affiliation: demonstrated repeatedly in social network analysis literature.\n\nPrivacy-preserving techniques that partially mitigate inference attacks: (1) Differential privacy — adds calibrated noise to outputs, providing formal ε-indistinguishability guarantees at cost of utility; (2) Federated learning — model training without raw data centralisation, reducing the surface for inference attacks; (3) k-anonymity / l-diversity — requires each individual to be indistinguishable from k-1 others, but vulnerable to composition attacks.\n\nRegulatory frameworks are attempting to account for inference risk: GDPR Recital 26 defines personal data by reference to re-identifiability ('reasonably likely' test); California Privacy Rights Act (CPRA) extends sensitive data categories to inferred sensitive attributes. The gap between regulatory intent and technical enforcement remains large — most data controllers do not model the inference space of their data collections.",
    },
  },

  "synthetic-media": {
    term: "Synthetic Media and Deepfakes",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "Synthetic media means video, audio, or images that were created or manipulated by AI to look or sound real. Deepfakes are the most famous type: AI-generated video that shows a real person doing or saying something they never did. Voice cloning is the audio version: a model trained on someone's voice that can say anything in their voice.\n\nThe technology has moved from expensive and rare to cheap and fast. As of 2026, commercial services can clone a convincing voice from three seconds of audio. You cannot assume that a phone call is from who it sounds like. You cannot assume that a video is real because it looks real.\n\nThis does not mean everything is fake. It means you need a different framework for evidence: where did this come from, who authenticated it, and is there a way to verify it from a source I trust independently — not just from the content itself?",
      standard:
        "Synthetic media encompasses AI-generated or AI-manipulated video, audio, and images — most publicly known through 'deepfakes' (face-swapped video using generative adversarial networks or diffusion models) and voice cloning (neural text-to-speech synthesis trained on a target speaker). The generation quality and accessibility of these tools has advanced rapidly: as of 2026, voice cloning from 3-second audio samples and photorealistic face synthesis are available via commercial APIs.\n\nThe practical implications are several. First, social engineering: voice-cloning scams (calls from apparent family members in distress) are documented at scale; video deepfakes have been used in financial fraud (a Hong Kong company was deceived into transferring $25 million via a deepfake video call in 2024). Second, evidence reliability: the evidentiary value of audio and video is declining, with legal and journalistic standards beginning to require technical authentication. Third, reputation and political harm: deepfakes of public figures are used to spread disinformation and create false impressions of statements or actions.\n\nDetection approaches — GAN-fingerprint analysis, spectral artefact detection, physiological inconsistency detection — have not kept pace with generation quality. The most robust practical defence is provenance verification rather than artefact detection: C2PA (Content Credentials) cryptographic provenance metadata enables authentic media to carry unforgeable records of creation, but adoption is not yet universal.",
      technical:
        "Synthetic media generation operates across several architectures. Face synthesis and video manipulation use GANs (StyleGAN3, DALL-E variants) and increasingly diffusion-based models (Stable Video Diffusion, Sora). Voice cloning uses encoder-decoder transformer architectures: VALL-E (Microsoft, 2023) demonstrated zero-shot voice synthesis from 3-second prompts by encoding speaker characteristics as conditioning embeddings; ElevenLabs, XTTS, and similar commercial systems offer production-quality voice cloning.\n\nDetection methods and their limitations: (1) GAN fingerprint analysis — specific artefacts in GAN-generated images (spectral signatures, blending boundaries) are detectable but become less reliable as generation quality improves and as images are JPEG-compressed or resized. (2) Physiological signal detection — rPPG (remote photoplethysmography) detects absence of realistic skin colour variation due to blood flow; HeartForge and similar tools leverage this. (3) Neural classifiers trained on deepfake datasets — generalise poorly to new generation methods.\n\nAuthentication alternatives are more robust than detection: C2PA (Coalition for Content Provenance and Authenticity) defines a standard for cryptographic provenance metadata that travels with media files, enabling receivers to verify creation origin. SynthID (Google DeepMind) embeds imperceptible watermarks at generation time. Both approaches require adoption at the generation and distribution layer — they solve provenance, not detection of unmarked fakes.\n\nLegal landscape as of 2026: no comprehensive US federal deepfake legislation; state-level laws cover non-consensual intimate imagery (NCII) deepfakes and election-related deepfakes. EU AI Act Article 50 requires disclosure labelling for AI-generated content. Active case law under defamation, IIED, and CFAA in various jurisdictions.",
    },
  },

  "algorithmic-credit": {
    term: "Algorithmic Credit and Financial Scoring",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "Algorithmic credit scoring means a computer decides whether you can borrow money, rent an apartment, or get insurance — in milliseconds, based on data patterns, without a human reading your application.\n\nThese systems are everywhere and mostly invisible. When you apply for a credit card and get an answer in 30 seconds, an algorithm decided. When your insurance quote comes back higher than your neighbour's, an algorithm priced you differently. When your rental application is flagged before a human sees it, an algorithm scored you.\n\nTwo things worth knowing: First, if you are declined for credit using consumer report data, you have a legal right to an adverse action notice stating the main reasons — most people don't know this. Second, these systems can encode bias from historical data. If the historical data reflects past discrimination, the algorithm reproduces it — and you can't argue with an algorithm the way you can argue with a loan officer.",
      standard:
        "Algorithmic credit and financial scoring uses machine learning models to evaluate creditworthiness, insurance risk, and rental eligibility. These systems have largely replaced human loan officers for most standard credit decisions — they operate at scale and speed that human review cannot match, and they are largely invisible to the people they affect.\n\nFeature inputs have expanded significantly beyond traditional credit bureau data (payment history, utilisation, length of history). Fintech lenders now use: purchase patterns, bank account cashflow metadata, device type and behaviour, location patterns, and in some markets, social network indicators. Many of these features are not disclosed to applicants and serve as proxies for demographic attributes that are legally protected against direct discrimination.\n\nKnow your rights: in the US, the Fair Credit Reporting Act (FCRA) requires that any adverse credit decision based on consumer report data include an adverse action notice identifying the principal factors. The Equal Credit Opportunity Act (ECOA) extends rights to know the specific reasons for denial. Most people do not know these rights exist — and exercising them starts a clock on the creditor's obligation to respond.\n\nThe core bias risk: when models are trained on historical financial data, they encode the patterns of historical lending decisions, including patterns of geographic and demographic discrimination. A model predicting 'creditworthiness' based on patterns of who was previously extended credit will reproduce the biases of those lending decisions — faster, at larger scale, and with less individual accountability than human loan officers.",
      technical:
        "Algorithmic credit scoring applies supervised ML — typically gradient-boosted trees (XGBoost, LightGBM) or deep learning models — to binary or continuous creditworthiness prediction. Feature engineering has expanded from traditional credit bureau variables (FICO components: payment history, amounts owed, length of history, new credit, credit mix) to alternative data: transaction-level banking data, telco bill payment, rental payment history, device metadata, and in some international markets, psychometric and behavioural signals.\n\nRegulatory framework (US): FCRA governs use of consumer report data in credit decisions; adverse action notices must identify principal reasons in human-interpretable form. ECOA prohibits disparate treatment on protected characteristics and, under disparate impact doctrine, facially neutral practices with discriminatory effects. CFPB's 2023 guidance on ECOA adverse action requires principal reasons even for complex ML models — creating interpretability requirements. The OCC, FDIC, and Fed have issued joint guidance on model risk management (SR 11-7) applicable to credit models.\n\nFairness and interpretability tensions: high-performing credit models (gradient-boosted trees, neural networks) tend to be less interpretable than linear models, creating regulatory compliance tension. SHAP-based adverse action explanations are technically feasible but may not reflect the causal structure of model predictions. Disparate impact testing requires demographic data that models are often not permitted to use directly, requiring post-hoc audit with external demographic data. Formal fairness criteria (demographic parity vs. equalised odds vs. calibration) are mathematically incompatible when base rates differ across groups — deployers must make explicit normative choices about which criterion to optimise.",
    },
  },

  "generative-ai": {
    term: "Generative AI",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "Generative AI is AI that creates new things — text, images, video, code, music — rather than just classifying or finding things. When you ask ChatGPT to write a paragraph, or use an AI image tool to make a picture, or use a coding assistant to write a function, you are using generative AI.\n\nIt generates by learning patterns from massive amounts of existing content, then producing something new that fits those patterns. The result often looks genuinely original. But it is always built from the statistical structure of what it was trained on — which is why it can be creative and wrong at the same time.\n\nThe key question to ask about any generative AI output: is this plausible-sounding, or is this true? Generative AI optimises for plausibility. Truth is a separate question that requires a separate check.",
      standard:
        "Generative AI refers to machine learning systems trained to produce novel outputs — text, images, audio, video, code — rather than classifying, predicting, or retrieving. The dominant architectures are large language models (text and code), diffusion models (images and audio), and increasingly multimodal systems that handle multiple content types from a single model.\n\nGenerative AI raises issues distinct from analytical AI. First, output quality is genuinely variable — from excellent to subtly wrong to completely fabricated — with no reliable internal signal distinguishing these. The model optimises for plausibility, not accuracy, and plausibility is often indistinguishable from truth without independent verification. Second, attribution and ownership are contested: generated content is derived from training data patterns, creating copyright questions about training inputs and generated outputs that are actively being decided in courts. Third, misuse is structurally easier: generative AI dramatically lowers the cost of creating misleading content, synthetic media, and persuasive disinformation at scale.\n\nThe professional habit generative AI requires is fundamentally different from other software: the output is a first draft that requires expert review, not a function that returns a correct answer. Every domain where the cost of error is high — legal, medical, financial, journalistic — requires a verification layer that generative AI itself cannot provide.",
      technical:
        "Generative AI encompasses several technically distinct paradigms: (1) Autoregressive language models (GPT-4, Claude 3, Gemini) using next-token prediction p(x_t | x_{<t}) over discrete BPE vocabularies, scaled to 10¹²+ training tokens. (2) Latent diffusion models (Stable Diffusion 3, DALL-E 3, Imagen) performing iterative denoising in a compressed latent space ε-θ(z_t, t, c), conditioned on text embeddings from a frozen text encoder (CLIP, T5). (3) Flow-matching models (Flux, Stable Audio 2) using continuous normalising flows for more efficient high-quality generation. (4) Multimodal architectures (GPT-4V, Gemini Ultra, LLaVA) unifying modalities through shared embedding spaces or cross-modal attention.\n\nTraining paradigms: CLIP-style contrastive pre-training aligns image and text embeddings; diffusion models use denoising score matching; LLMs use cross-entropy loss on next-token prediction; post-training alignment via RLHF or DPO shapes output distributions toward human-preferred responses.\n\nCapability boundaries and failure modes: hallucination rates remain non-trivial across all frontier models; temporal consistency in video generation is an active research problem; compositional generalisation (reliably handling novel combinations of concepts) is demonstrably weaker than it appears from selective examples; model self-evaluation of output quality is unreliable. Key research frontiers: multi-modal reasoning, video generation at production quality, controllable generation with formal guarantees, and mechanistic interpretability of generative behaviour.",
    },
  },

  // ── MODULE 2 VOCABULARY ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  "tool-selection-framework": {
    term: "AI Tool Selection Framework",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "With new AI tools launching every week, the question 'which AI tools are best?' has an expiration date of about 30 days. The skill worth learning is not the list — it is the five questions you ask about any tool before you trust your work to it.\n\nThe five dimensions: (1) Data sovereignty — does your data stay under your control, or does the provider use it for training? (2) Hallucination risk for your use case — how often does this type of tool produce confident wrong answers on the specific task you need? (3) Integration cost — what technical and organisational effort does adoption require? (4) Human-in-loop design — does the tool make it easy to review and correct its outputs, or does it deliver finished-seeming results that bury errors? (5) Update frequency — how often does the provider change the model, and do those changes require you to re-validate your use case?\n\nIn 2023, Samsung engineers pasted proprietary source code into ChatGPT to get debugging help. The data was sent to OpenAI's servers and could be used for training under the terms in place at the time. Samsung had not checked the data sovereignty dimension. The code contained trade secrets. The outcome: Samsung banned public LLMs for internal work entirely. The tool was useful. The dimension check was skipped.\n\nA framework like this works on tools you have never seen before. A catalogue of 'top tools' is obsolete before you finish reading it.",
      standard:
        "A tool-selection framework solves a structural problem: the AI tool landscape changes faster than any catalogue can track. A principled 5-dimension framework evaluates any tool — including ones that did not exist when you learned the framework — against the properties that consistently determine whether adoption causes regret.\n\nThe five dimensions are chosen to surface problems at the 6–12 month horizon, not at demo time. At demo time, every tool looks good: the salesperson controls the scenario, the tool performs its strongest task, and the dimensions that will matter in production are invisible. The framework reverses this by asking: which dimension, if it degraded after adoption, would cost the most?\n\n(1) Data sovereignty — Does your input data leave your control? Does it become training data? Who can access it? This is the dimension most often skipped and most often regretted. The Samsung (2023) incident — engineers pasting proprietary source code into a public LLM, inadvertently sharing trade secrets — is the canonical case. Audit the terms of service and the enterprise data agreement before you adopt, not after.\n\n(2) Hallucination risk for the use case — Not 'does this tool hallucinate?' (all generative tools do). But: does this tool hallucinate on the specific task you need, at a rate your verification process can catch? Hallucination risk is use-case-dependent. A tool with high hallucination risk on medical fact retrieval may have acceptable performance on email drafting where errors are self-evident.\n\n(3) Integration cost — What is the all-in cost: API integration, data pipeline changes, staff training, workflow redesign, change management? Integration cost is almost always underestimated at selection time, because demo costs are zero and real-world deployment costs are not.\n\n(4) Human-in-loop design — Does the tool surface uncertainty, present options, and make review easy? Or does it deliver polished-looking outputs that discourage scrutiny? Tools that hide their work (black-box outputs, no confidence signals, no prompt visibility) systematically increase the risk that errors pass undetected. A tool that hides the prompt layer entirely also removes the user's ability to iterate.\n\n(5) Update frequency — A tool that is updated frequently has fresh capabilities — and requires fresh validation. An update can change the model's behaviour on your exact use case. High update frequency requires ongoing monitoring. Low update frequency risks stale performance. Neither is inherently better — the question is whether your workflow has the validation cadence to match the update frequency.\n\nThe framework is a tradeoff map, not a pass/fail checklist. Every real tool is strong on some dimensions and weak on others. The skill is identifying which weaknesses matter for your specific context.",
      technical:
        "AI tool selection is a multi-attribute decision problem under uncertainty, where the relevant attributes are those that predict post-adoption regret rather than pre-adoption appeal. The 5-dimension framework operationalises this by targeting properties that are (a) empirically associated with deployment failures and (b) assessable with reasonable effort pre-adoption.\n\nDimension 1 — Data sovereignty: Formalised as: does the vendor have contractual or technical access to inference-time inputs beyond the immediate inference request? Relevant sub-dimensions: (a) inference logging (scope, duration, access controls); (b) training data pipeline — whether inputs are retained for model improvement; (c) data residency — whether data transits or is stored in regulated jurisdictions; (d) deletion rights — ability to request input deletion and independent verification that deletion occurred. The Samsung (2023) incident demonstrates that data sovereignty failures are not technical events — they are governance failures triggered by mismatch between assumed and actual terms of service.\n\nDimension 2 — Hallucination risk for use case: Hallucination rates are not intrinsic to a model — they are a function of the model × task interaction. Evaluation against your specific use case requires domain-appropriate benchmarks or red-teaming. For high-stakes use cases (clinical decision support, legal research, financial analysis), minimum requirement is: documented hallucination rate on analogous tasks, failure mode characterisation (types of error), and a user-accessible verification pathway for every output type.\n\nDimension 3 — Integration cost: Total cost of ownership includes API/SDK integration, data pipeline modifications, access control implementation, output monitoring setup, staff training, workflow redesign, and ongoing validation burden. Underestimation is structural: vendors optimise demos for ease, suppressing visibility of real integration complexity. The reference class for AI integration projects in enterprises suggests 3–5× multiplier on vendor-estimated integration time.\n\nDimension 4 — Human-in-loop design: Characterise whether the tool's UX architecture supports or suppresses review. Key signals: does the tool surface uncertainty estimates (calibration quality)? Does it expose intermediate reasoning (enabling error localisation)? Does it make prompt and context visible (enabling iteration)? Does it deliver outputs in a format that encourages review (structured, with attributions) or discourages it (polished, authoritative-appearing prose)? Tools scoring poorly on this dimension systematically increase type-2 errors (errors that are missed) relative to type-1 errors (errors that prompt review).\n\nDimension 5 — Update frequency: Model updates are not versioned the same way traditional software releases are. Silent updates (changes to RLHF reward models, system prompts, fine-tuning data) can change model behaviour on production use cases without API version changes. Evaluation cadence must be aligned with update frequency. For regulated applications (EU AI Act Annex III high-risk categories), model updates may trigger conformity re-assessment obligations.",
    },
  },

  "failure-modes": {
    term: "The 7 AI Failure Modes",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "There are not a hundred ways an AI can be wrong. There are seven, and every bad output from a real AI tool is one or more of them. Learning to name them is the difference between 'AI can be wrong' (not useful) and 'this is false precision — it's real data, just stated with more certainty than the evidence supports' (useful — you know what to fix and how).\n\nThe seven: (1) Hallucination — the model invents content that doesn't exist. (2) Outdated information — the model's training ended months or years ago; it doesn't know what happened since. (3) Sycophancy — the model agrees with you and tells you what you want to hear instead of what is true. (4) Scope drift — the model answers a slightly different question than the one you asked. (5) False precision — real information, but stated with more certainty than the evidence supports. (6) Context blindness — the model applies a general pattern when your specific situation needed different reasoning. (7) Bias amplification — the model reproduces stereotypes or skewed patterns from its training data.\n\nThree things matter most about this list: First, different failure modes need different fixes. Hallucination is reduced by checking sources; sycophancy is reduced by asking the model to argue against itself; false precision is reduced by asking for confidence ranges. 'The AI was wrong' doesn't tell you what to do. 'That was false precision' does. Second, a single output can exhibit multiple failure modes at once — one paragraph might be both sycophantic and scope-drifted. Third, asking the AI to check its own output doesn't catch sycophancy — it makes it worse.",
      standard:
        "The 7 Failure Modes taxonomy provides a diagnostic vocabulary for AI output evaluation. Every failure mode traces to a single design fact: LLMs are optimised to produce outputs that look right, not outputs that are right. Fluency and truth are separate properties. Each failure mode is a specific way that separation becomes visible.\n\n(1) Hallucination — the model generates content that is plausible but factually false or entirely fabricated: citations that don't exist, events that didn't happen, statistics that were invented. Mechanism: next-token generation optimises for plausibility, not accuracy. Mitigation: verify against primary sources; use retrieval-augmented systems that ground outputs in cited documents.\n\n(2) Outdated information — the model's knowledge ends at its training cutoff. It cannot know about events, publications, legal changes, or product updates that occurred after that date. And crucially, it may confabulate plausible-sounding current information rather than disclosing its ignorance. Mitigation: check the training cutoff; treat any time-sensitive claim as requiring external verification.\n\n(3) Sycophancy — the model prioritises agreement and validation over accuracy. Ask a leading question and the model confirms it. Assert a false premise and the model accommodates it. Push back on a correct answer and the model may reverse itself without new evidence. Mitigation: ask the model to argue the opposite case; test whether the model maintains its position under social pressure.\n\n(4) Scope drift — the model answers a related but different question than the one you asked. Often the model migrates toward a question it can answer more confidently. The answer is fluent and correct — it's just the answer to a slightly different question. Mitigation: explicitly restate the required scope; use structured prompts that constrain the answer domain.\n\n(5) False precision — the model states real information with greater specificity or confidence than the evidence supports. 'This approach improves conversion by 23%' — real finding, wrong level of confidence; actual research showed 15–35% range. Mitigation: ask for confidence ranges and source quality; treat specific percentages and statistics as soft until verified.\n\n(6) Context blindness — the model applies a general pattern to a specific situation where that pattern doesn't apply. The general advice is correct; your situation is an exception. Mitigation: provide explicit context about what makes your situation different; ask the model to identify assumptions it made about your context.\n\n(7) Bias amplification — the model reproduces stereotypes and skewed patterns encoded in its training data. In image generation: CEO is a white man. In hiring analysis: 'strong' candidates match historical patterns that reflect past discrimination. Mitigation: audit outputs across demographic groups; explicitly prompt for diversity or specify that stereotypical associations should be avoided.\n\nThe taxonomy matters because the mitigation is mode-specific. A prompt strategy that catches hallucination may not catch sycophancy — and may make it worse. Accurate diagnosis is the prerequisite for effective correction.",
      technical:
        "The 7 Failure Modes taxonomy provides a mechanistic classification of LLM output failures grounded in the properties of transformer-based generative models. Each mode has a distinct causal account linking it to specific aspects of model architecture, training objective, or deployment context.\n\n(1) Hallucination — Output tokens with high model probability but low factual accuracy. Cause: next-token prediction optimises p(token | context), which is a fluency objective, not a factual accuracy objective. The model has no internal truth-checker; confidence in generation is decoupled from reliability of content. Relevant research: Maynez et al. (2020) on faithfulness in summarisation; Mallen et al. (2022) on entity-level hallucination rate by entity frequency. Mitigation: RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation) grounds generation in retrieved documents, reducing open-domain hallucination by providing factual anchors in context.\n\n(2) Outdated information — A temporal boundary condition, not a generation failure. The model's parametric knowledge is frozen at training cutoff. Exacerbated by the fact that LLMs do not have reliable self-knowledge of this boundary — they may generate confident-sounding current claims about events they have no data on. Mitigation: RAG, web-search augmentation, or explicit in-context provision of current information.\n\n(3) Sycophancy — RLHF-induced alignment failure (see vocabulary entry for sycophancy). Mechanism: reward models trained on human preference ratings systematically prefer agreeable, validating responses, creating a training signal that incentivises position capitulation under social pressure. Perez et al. (2022) and subsequent work demonstrate consistent sycophantic behaviour across model families. Mitigation: adversarial prompting ('steelman the opposing view'), multi-turn pressure testing, constitutional AI interventions that penalise position reversal without new evidence.\n\n(4) Scope drift — The model performs query reformulation, migrating from the asked question to a more answerable related question. This can be construed as a form of in-context rationalisation: the model has stronger parametric signal about a related question and generates in the direction of maximum signal. Distinct from hallucination because the output content may be factually correct — the failure is the mapping between question asked and question answered. Detection requires external comparison of question and answer scope; mitigation requires explicit scope-bounding in the prompt.\n\n(5) False precision — Epistemic overconfidence: outputs that assert specific quantitative or qualitative claims with confidence levels exceeding what the training data or reasoning chain supports. Related to but distinct from hallucination: the underlying fact may exist, but the confidence level is wrong. Caused by the absence of calibrated uncertainty propagation in autoregressive generation — the model does not track uncertainty through its reasoning chain. Mitigation: explicit prompts requesting confidence ranges and source quality levels; calibration evaluation against known reference points.\n\n(6) Context blindness — Distribution mismatch between the model's learned patterns and the user's specific context. The model applies a general heuristic that is correct for the training distribution but incorrect for the user's particular situation. Structural cause: models cannot reliably represent 'this situation is unusual in a way that invalidates my general pattern'. Mitigation: explicit contextualisation in the prompt; asking the model to enumerate assumptions made about context before answering.\n\n(7) Bias amplification — Systematic reproduction of stereotyped associations encoded in training corpora. Mechanism: word embedding geometry and attention patterns encode statistical co-occurrences from training data; if 'CEO' was predominantly associated with male-presenting faces or first names in training data, that association is reproduced in generation. Bolukbasi et al. (2016) documented analogous bias in word2vec; subsequent work confirmed persistence in instruction-tuned LLMs. Mitigation: post-hoc debiasing, contrastive prompting, fine-tuning on balanced datasets, and explicit diversity requirements in the prompt.",
    },
    analogy:
      "Think of the 7 failure modes as the seven ways a very knowledgeable but flawed colleague can mislead you: they can make things up (hallucination), be out of date (outdated info), tell you what you want to hear (sycophancy), answer a nearby question instead of yours (scope drift), be overconfident (false precision), miss what makes your situation special (context blindness), or reproduce patterns that are statistically common but wrong for your case (bias amplification). You don't diagnose a colleague by saying 'they were wrong' — you figure out which of these things happened, because that tells you how to fix it.",
  },

  "chain-of-thought": {
    term: "Chain-of-Thought Prompting",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "Chain-of-thought prompting means asking an AI to show its reasoning before giving you the answer. Instead of 'What is the answer to X?', you ask 'Think through this step by step before answering.' This sounds like a small change. The improvement in quality on complex tasks is not small.\n\nWhy does it work? LLMs generate text one word at a time. When they jump straight to a conclusion, any error in the reasoning that got there is invisible — it gets baked silently into the answer. When the model has to write out its reasoning first, that reasoning appears in the text you can read. Errors become visible. The model also seems to 'think better' when it's working through intermediate steps, the same way you might work better when writing notes versus holding everything in your head.\n\nThe research backing this is specific: a 2022 paper by Kojima and colleagues showed that just adding 'Let's think step by step' — no examples, no elaborate setup — substantially improved performance on multi-step arithmetic and logical reasoning. You don't need a magic formula. You need to ask the model to reason before concluding.\n\nThe three-turn pattern takes this further: Turn 1, ask for the answer. Turn 2, ask 'find the three weakest claims in what you just wrote and explain why they are weak.' Turn 3, ask for a revised answer addressing those weaknesses. This is the difference between a good first draft and something you would stake your name on.",
      standard:
        "Chain-of-thought (CoT) prompting is the practice of eliciting intermediate reasoning steps from a language model before it generates a conclusion. It is one of the highest-ROI prompt techniques known: a simple natural-language instruction to 'think step by step' or 'reason through this before answering' consistently improves performance on tasks requiring multi-step arithmetic, logical deduction, and compositional reasoning.\n\nThe mechanism is architectural. LLMs generate output token by token. At each step, only the previously generated tokens are available as context. A model that jumps straight to a conclusion lacks visible intermediate steps — any reasoning error that occurred implicitly gets silently incorporated into the output. When the model instead generates intermediate reasoning tokens explicitly, those tokens become part of the context for subsequent generation. The model has more 'room to think', errors can propagate through visible (and therefore catchable) reasoning steps, and the final output is conditioned on more reasoning context rather than jumping from prompt to conclusion.\n\nKey research findings:\n— Wei et al. (2022) showed CoT prompting emerges as a capability at large model scale (100B+ parameters) and substantially improves accuracy on GSM8K (grade school math), SVAMP, and BigBench Hard reasoning tasks.\n— Kojima et al. (2022) showed that zero-shot CoT — adding only 'Let's think step by step' with no examples — works across multiple model families and task types. This is the direct practical implication: you don't need few-shot examples to get CoT benefits.\n\nThe three-turn iteration pattern builds on CoT:\n— Turn 1: broad generation ('Summarise the key findings from this document and their implications')\n— Turn 2: structured critique ('Find the three weakest claims in what you just produced and explain specifically why each is weak')\n— Turn 3: targeted revision ('Now revise the output, addressing the weaknesses you identified')\n\nTurn 2 is the critical step. Without it, Turn 3 revision simply restates the original answer with more words. With it, the model is forced to take an adversarial stance toward its own output — temporarily breaking the sycophantic loop and generating a higher-quality revision.\n\nContext-window note: the 'lost in the middle' phenomenon (Liu et al., 2023) means that long prompts are not equally attended to. Critical constraints and examples should go near the beginning or end of a prompt, not buried in the middle.",
      technical:
        "Chain-of-thought prompting exploits the autoregressive generation property to externalise and condition on intermediate reasoning steps. In standard generation, the model computes p(answer | prompt) in a single step, which collapses multi-step reasoning into a single implicit mapping. CoT reformulates this as p(answer | prompt, reasoning_trace) where the reasoning_trace is itself generated by the model.\n\nFormal framing: standard generation maximises Σ log p(a_t | prompt, a_{<t}). CoT generation maximises Σ log p(r_t | prompt, r_{<t}) followed by Σ log p(a_t | prompt, r, a_{<t}), where r is the generated reasoning trace. The key mechanism: the probability distribution over answer tokens is conditioned on a richer context that includes the intermediate reasoning steps, not just the original prompt.\n\nEmergence properties: Wei et al. (2022) demonstrated that CoT benefits are sparse at small model scale and emerge sharply above approximately 100B parameters. This is consistent with the hypothesis that small models cannot generate coherent intermediate reasoning chains — their CoT tokens are effectively noise relative to any real reasoning steps. Kojima et al. (2022) demonstrated that zero-shot CoT (a single instruction trigger 'Let's think step by step') generalises across tasks and model families without requiring task-specific few-shot demonstrations.\n\nProcess reward models (PRMs): a research-stage refinement where a separate model is trained to evaluate the correctness of intermediate reasoning steps (not just final answers). Lightman et al. (2023) showed PRMs substantially outperform outcome reward models on multi-step math reasoning by catching errors mid-chain. This is an active frontier for improving CoT reliability.\n\nPrompt injection risk in CoT pipelines: when CoT reasoning is visible in the output, adversarial inputs can target the reasoning trace rather than the final answer. A malicious document included in the context can insert false premises into the reasoning chain that propagate to a manipulated conclusion — a variant of indirect prompt injection. This is a material security concern for any agentic pipeline where model reasoning is influenced by retrieved or user-provided content.\n\nContext-position effects (Liu et al., 2023 'Lost in the Middle'): attention in long-context models is not uniformly distributed. Recall of information at mid-context positions is significantly lower than at prefix/suffix positions. Practical implication: for prompts combining instructions, examples, and retrieved context, high-priority instructions should be positioned at the system prompt prefix or immediately before the final generation instruction.",
    },
    analogy:
      "Writing out your work on a math test versus just putting down the answer. When you write the work, you and the teacher can both see exactly where an error crept in. When you just write the answer, wrong is wrong with no diagnostic information. LLMs 'think better' when they write their work for the same reason you do: the intermediate steps are visible, catchable, and correctable.",
  },

  "human-in-loop": {
    term: "Human-in-the-Loop Design",
    glosses: {
      plain:
        "Human-in-the-loop means deliberately putting a human review step at the right moments in an AI workflow — not just at the beginning or end, but at the specific points where AI failure is most likely or most consequential.\n\nThe worst AI workflows are 'human at the front, machine the rest of the way': a person writes a prompt, the AI produces something, it ships. No review of the output. No checkpoint at the point where the failure mode most likely entered.\n\nGood human-in-the-loop design is specific. It asks: which failure mode is most predictable at each step of this workflow? Then it places a human review there, not everywhere (which isn't feasible) and not nowhere (which is negligent). A health-information workflow places a human review before any recommendation, because sycophancy and hallucination combine dangerously in that context. A legal drafting workflow places a review at the claim-verification step, because false precision and outdated information are the failure modes most likely there. The checkpoint placement follows the failure mode map.\n\nThe concept comes from automation engineering: 'human-in-the-loop' originally meant a human who can intervene in a physical control system before the system acts. Applied to AI, it means designing workflows where AI handles the high-volume, well-defined parts, and humans handle the judgment, verification, and accountability that AI systems cannot provide reliably.",
      standard:
        "Human-in-the-loop (HITL) design refers to the deliberate placement of human review and judgment at specific points in AI-assisted workflows, particularly at points where AI failure is predictable or where the cost of undetected error is high.\n\nThe concept has a useful taxonomy: Human-in-the-loop (HITL) — human must review and approve every AI output before action. Human-on-the-loop (HOTL) — human monitors AI outputs and can intervene, but the system acts by default without explicit approval. Human-out-of-the-loop (HOOTL) — fully automated system with no routine human review. These are not ranked — the appropriate level depends on the task's error cost, volume, and time constraints.\n\nPrinciple-based checkpoint design: the most effective HITL implementations do not place a human at every step (infeasible at scale) or only at the final output (catching errors too late, after they have propagated through multiple AI generation steps). Instead, checkpoints are placed where the 7 failure modes are most predictable and most consequential for that workflow.\n\nExamples of failure-mode-driven checkpoints: A summarisation workflow should have a human review at the claim-attribution step, not just the formatting step, because hallucination and false precision are the predictable failure modes in summarisation. A customer-communication drafting workflow should have a human review before any claim-specific statements (pricing, policy, availability) because these are the high-hallucination-risk claim types. A research synthesis workflow should have a human check the retrieved citations against the cited claims, because citation hallucination is the dominant failure mode in long-form research generation.\n\nHITL and skill heterogeneity: a human checkpoint is only as valuable as the reviewer's ability to catch the failure mode it is designed to intercept. A junior reviewer may not catch false precision on complex financial claims; a domain expert will. Workflow design must account for the skill level of the human-in-the-loop, not just the presence of a human.\n\nRegulatory context: the EU AI Act Annex III categories of 'high-risk AI' applications — health, employment, education, essential services, law enforcement, migration, democratic processes — all require human oversight by design as a condition of lawful deployment. The HITL requirement is not just a best practice; it is a legal obligation for consequential applications in regulated contexts.",
      technical:
        "Human-in-the-loop design in AI systems operationalises the principle that human judgment should be inserted at workflow positions where AI failure probability exceeds acceptable thresholds, where failure consequences are above acceptable risk levels, or where regulatory requirements mandate human oversight.\n\nFormal HITL taxonomy (Monarch, 2021): (1) Human-in-the-loop — human approval gates every inference-to-action step; (2) Human-on-the-loop — human monitors aggregate outputs and can interrupt, but default is automated action; (3) Human-out-of-the-loop — fully automated pipeline. Selection across these levels is a risk-calibrated decision: HITL is appropriate when per-inference error cost is high and volume permits human review cadence; HOTL is appropriate when error cost is moderate and individual review is not feasible at volume; HOOTL is appropriate only when error cost is low or failure mode risk is demonstrably bounded.\n\nCheckpoint placement methodology: failure-mode-driven checkpoint design requires (a) a failure mode taxonomy for the workflow (which of the 7 failure modes is most likely at each step), (b) a consequence model (what is the cost of an undetected instance of each failure mode), and (c) a probability estimate for each mode at each step. Checkpoints are placed where expected cost-of-failure exceeds review cost: E[cost_failure × p_failure] > cost_review.\n\nSkill-matching requirements: HITL adds value only when the human reviewer can actually detect the failure mode the checkpoint is designed to catch. This creates skill-calibration requirements: a reviewer checking for hallucinated citations must be able to perform the lookup; a reviewer checking for false precision in statistical claims must have domain-adequate quantitative literacy. Workflow documentation should specify the reviewer competency required for each checkpoint, not just that 'a human reviews'.\n\nEU AI Act HITL requirements (Annex III, Article 14): high-risk AI systems must be designed so that natural persons can effectively oversee them. Specific requirements: (a) human oversight measures built into the system design; (b) ability to interrupt or override the system; (c) capability to perform meaningful review (not rubber-stamping). The Act distinguishes meaningful oversight from nominal oversight — a human approving outputs they cannot evaluate does not satisfy Article 14.\n\nFeedback loop design: HITL review generates a data stream of human corrections that can be used for model improvement (RLHF-style), error rate monitoring (detect drift), and audit trails (maintain accountability records). Effective HITL design captures this feedback — it does not just intercept errors, it learns from them.",
    },
  },
};
